            "command": "git commit --author=\"John Wiegley <johnw@newartisans.com>\" -m \"$(cat <<'EOF'\nfix(query): preserve multi-word account names in auto-xact predicates\n\nWhen a journal file contains an automated transaction with an unquoted\naccount name that has embedded spaces, e.g.:\n\n    = income:b c\n        liabilities:a  -1\n\nthe query lexer was tokenizing the predicate string with space as a\nseparator (multiple_args=false mode), producing two TERM tokens\n\"income:b\" and \"c\" that were implicitly OR-ed.  The token \"c\" then\nmatched unintended accounts (e.g. \"assets:cash\"), causing the\nauto-xact to fire on both the intended posting and its balancing\ncounterpart, with the two applications cancelling each other so the\nrule appeared to have no effect.\n\nFix: in the single-string tokenizer path (!multiple_args), when a space\nis encountered mid-identifier, peek ahead past the whitespace.  If the\nnext word is a recognized query keyword (and, or, not, expr, note, etc.)\nor a special operator character, stop the token as before.  Otherwise,\nabsorb the space as a single normalized space and continue accumulating,\nso \"income:b c\" becomes one TERM token whose mask matches \"income:b c\"\nexactly — identical to the quoted form \"= 'income:b c'\".\n\nBoolean operators between multi-word names continue to work:\n  = income:b c and income:d e   →  TERM(\"income:b c\") AND TERM(\"income:d e\")\n\nFixes #2019\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>\nEOF\n)\"",
